  {
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Hi Alex / @bobylito  \r\nok I see what you mean... I did not even notice the \"count\" in the starRating widget.\r\n\r\n**Assumption**\r\n\r\nthe majority of current implementations of the widget is wrong as they most likely use non-integer values for the widget. (you could do some sample checking among your customers that use this widget to see if this is the case)\r\n\r\n**Solutions**\r\n\r\nAssuming most people have implemented the widget with non-integers, I'd suggest making a breaking change when you release v2 for InstantSearch.js (btw, any timeline?) so that the default behavior of the starRating widget is to handle non-integers. The reason for doing this is to make sure that people won't miss this important detail in the future. This will mean that the count is dropped, but I think it's better to drop the count by default than having wrong results because people misunderstand how the widget works.\r\n\r\nYou can create a second widget for people who want the count all costs. I have no data to back it up, but I don't think that the count on the starRating is a must have as filtering on the stars simply means you want a certain quality, it doesn't matter how many there are.\r\n\r\nIf you could simple sample check some implementation and see what people do in practice you could make a more data-driven decision. \r\n\r\nhope it helps! \r\n",
